ød","1217":"1217","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","1294":"1294","Murthokston, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Skotland","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Skotland","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1185–1231":"1185–1231","–Female":"Overleden","1211–1236":"1211–1236","1217–1294":"1217–1294","1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Overleden","1217":"1217","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","1294":"1294","Murthokston, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Schotland","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Schotland","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1185–1231":"1185–1231","–Female":"Deceased","1211–1236":"1211–1236","1217–1294":"1217–1294","1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1217":"1217","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","1294":"1294","Murthokston, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (Down): habitational and ethnic name from Middle English <i>Scot</i> ‘man from Scotland’. There is no evidence that the surname denoted either of the earlier senses of <i>Scot</i> as ‘(Gaelic-speaking) Irishman’ or ‘man from Alba’, the Gaelic-speaking region of Scotland north of the river Forth. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Duncan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh , also used among people without Scottish connections. This was the name of a 7th-century Scottish saint (abbot of Iona) and two medieval kings of Scotland. The final ‐<i>n</i> in the Anglicized form seems to be the result of confusion with the Gaelic word <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ in the Latinized form <i>Duncanus</i>.  Compare Irish  Donagh ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donnchadh","meanings":["Gaelic: compound of Old Celtic <i>donn</i> ‘brown’ + <i>chadh</i> ‘chief’ or ‘noble’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Duncan Scott of Murthockston was born in 1185, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Michael Scott of Rankilburn, was 23 and his mother, Margaret Syras, was 20. He married Mrs. Duncan Scott in 1210, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1231, in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 46, and was buried in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland."},"et":{"1185–1231":"1185–1231","–Female":"Surnud","1211–1236":"1211–1236","1217–1294":"1217–1294","1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1217":"1217","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","1294":"1294","Murthokston, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1185–1231":"1185–1231","–Female":"Kuollut","1211–1236":"1211–1236","1217–1294":"1217–1294","1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1217":"1217